iStock (iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories He may be shaky on his feet and nearing 93 - but longtime Zimbabwe president Robert Mugabe is the ruling party's pick for polls in less than two years' time AND he'll win. That is state media's line anyway.Harare - Zimbabwe has imported over 100 000 tons of maize worth $12.7m since October last year, Finance Minister Patrick Chinamasa has said, according to a report on Tuesday.According to the state-owned Chronicle newspaper, Chinamasa said the government would use a further $3.3m to deliver the maize to vulnerable families around the country.The maize was imported under the country's drought relief programme, aimed at assisting vulnerable families with food.&nbsp;Zimbabwe reportedly needs at least 1.8 million tons of maize a year to feed people and animals.According to reports at the beginning of the year, the&nbsp;southern parts of the country were left with less than 8&nbsp;weeks' supply of maize, forcing millers to urge government to grant permission for&nbsp;imports.Chinamasa said that the government had committed itself to importing at least 700&nbsp;000 tons of maize between October 2015-December 2016. He said the distribution of the maize to the vulnerable families across the country stood at about 94 300 metric tons against a target of at least 120&nbsp;000 metric tons. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.